'''Héctor del Curto''' is an [[Argentine tango]] [[bandoneon]] player.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jazz improv, Volume 7, Issues 3-4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1XAKAQAAMAAJ|year=2007|publisher=E.S. Proteus|page=191|quote="Revirado" is a delightful Astor Piazzola tango featuring Hector Del Curto on bandoneon.}}</ref> Born in [[Buenos Aires]], he began to study tango music at a young age, winning the Best Bandoneon under 25 when only 17 years old. Following that honor, he played with the late tango giants [[Ástor Piazzolla]] and [[Osvaldo Pugliese]] among many others. During this time, he played at the [[Kennedy Center]] and [[Carnegie Hall]].
In 2018 he won the [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Jazz Album]] for the album [[Jazz Tango]] as a member of the [[Pablo Ziegler]] Trio.<ref>{{cite web|title=60th Grammy Nominees|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/60th-annual-grammy-awards|website=Grammy.com|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref>
He currently resides in [[New York City]] where he founded the [[Eternal Tango]] orchestra and quartet.
