{{Infobox person | name = '''Oreoluwa Lesi''' | image =Oreoluwa Somolu Lesi.jpg | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = |spouse = |children = | death_date = | death_place = |residence = Lagos, Nigeria | nationality = Nigerian |net worth = | other_names = | known_for = {{hlist|Information Technology Literacy|Girls Empowerment }} | occupation = {{hlist||}} | Known for = | title = Executive director }}
'''Oreoluwa Lesi''' is a [[Nigerian]] entrepreneur and [[UK]]-trained economist and IT expert. She is the founder and executive director of [[Women's Technology Empowerment Centre]] (W.TEC), [[Nonprofit organization|a non-profit organisation]] that empowers women and girls socially and economically through education in Information technology.<ref name=vanguard>{{cite news|last1=Vista|first1=Woman|title=We’re empowering girls for IT devt – Oreoluwa Somolu|url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2012/10/were-empowering-girls-for-it-devt-oreoluwa-somolu/|accessdate=13 October 2016|publisher=Vanguard Newspaper|date=21 October 2012}}</ref> W.TEC was established in the year 2008. She is a fellow of [[Ashoka (non-profit organization)|Ashoka]] and a recipient of ABIE Award Winners, Change Agent.
==Early life and education==
Lesi's early years were spent in Nigeria. With an electrical engineer father, she fell in love with technology from childhood which led to her developing a software application that was used to run her parent's bookshop.<ref name=CP>{{cite web|last1=The Adminstrator|title=Ashoka Fellow|url=https://www.ashoka.org/en/fellow/oreoluwa-somolu#intro|publisher=Ashoka|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref>
After her years in high school at Queen's College, Lagos,<ref name=vanguard/> she studied diploma course in computer programming.<ref name=CP/> She proceeded to United Kingdom where she studied economics and graduated with bachelor's degree in economics from [[University of Essex]] She also obtained, master's degree in analysis, design and management information from [[London School of Economics and Political Science]].<ref name=lesi>{{cite web|last1=Bimbola Segun-Amag|title=CPAfrica Intervies Oreoluwa Somolu Lesi of Women's Technology Empowerment Centre|url=http://www.cp-africa.com/2015/07/31/cpafrica-interviews-oreoluwa-somolu-lesi-of-womens-technology-empowerment-centre/|publisher=CPAfrica|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref> Through her [[NGO]], she has touched live of 12000 girls in Nigeria.<ref name=lesi/> She studied Applied Sciences at [[Harvard University Extension School]]<ref name=Ore/>
==Career==
In the UK, she worked with Lonadek Oil and Gas Consultancy where she managed CSR Initiative-2020. She also worked with EDC in the United State on research project.She returned to Nigeria in the year 2005<ref name=lesi/> She established W.TEC in the year 2008.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Africa-ontherise|title=Exclusive Interview: Oreoluwa Somolu-Lesi, Executive Director, Women’s Technology Empowerment Centre (W.TEC)|url=http://www.africa-ontherise.com/2016/04/exclusive-interview-oreoluwa-somolu-lesi-executive-director-womens-technology-empowerment-centre-w-tec/|publisher=Changing the AFrican Conversation|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref> She was honored as fellow of Ashoka in 2013.<ref name=CP/> In 2009,She bagged ABIE Award Winners, Change Agent.<ref name=Ore>{{cite web|last1=The Editor|title=Anita Borg Institute Announces 2009 Change Agent Award Winners|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090826005160/en/Anita-Borg-Institute-Announces-2009-Change-Agent|publisher=Business Wire Institut|accessdate=17 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Jerri|first1=Barrett|title=ABIE Award Winners, Change Agent|url=https://anitaborg.org/profiles/abie-award-winners/oreoluwa-somolu/|publisher=Anita Borg Institute|accessdate=17 October 2016}}</ref>
==Personal life== She is married to Gboyega Lesi and resides in [[Lagos]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Odebiyi|first1=Olatunde|title=Compliment your wife always|url=http://thenationonlineng.net/complement-wife-always/|publisher=The Nation|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref>
